{"title_page": "Kuchesar Fort", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2019}}\n\n'''Kuchesar (\u0915\u0941\u091a\u0947\u0938\u0930) Fort''', also known as the '''Mud Fort''', was built as an [[opium]] trading depot in India in 1734. Many royal heirs stayed in the Kuchesar Fort as a means of furthering profits stemming from India, thus increasing the trading depot's popularity. Eventually government officials closed the fort due to a significant number of [[Death|deaths]] and [[Disease|illnesses]]. Many theorized that a heap of overgrowing plants were responsible for the \"unhealthy environment\". Recently, the locals of [[Kuchesar]] took the initiative to clear away the plants that once grew all over the building. It was restored and is now known as \"Mud Hotel\" in the state of [[Uttar Pradesh, India]], and acts as a tourist attraction for the city. \n\n==History==\nKuchesar Fort was the seat of the Jat Princely estate at [[Kuchesar]]<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.historyfiles.co.uk/KingListsFarEast/IndiaJatsMinorKings.htm|title=Kingdoms of South Asia - Minor Indian Kingdoms of the Jats|website=www.historyfiles.co.uk|access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref> during the [[Mughal Empire]] and the [[British Raj]]. The [[Jat people]] competed with the [[Maratha]]s, the [[Rohilla|Rohillas,]] French colonists, traders and explorers, as well as the [[British East India Company]] after the decline of the [[Mughal Empire]]. Kuchesar Fort was also a center for the Rai Brahmins, also called Bhatts \u2013 a branch of [[Kashmiri Brahmins]]. They were the Rajkavi of Kuchesar State (Rajkavis are similar to [[Poet laureate|poets laureate]]). Rai Moti Bhatt was the last Rajkavi of the Kuchesar State.\n\nThe rulers of Kuchesar built the fort in 1734 and maintained state population and awareness records. The fort was granted to Ramdhan Singh's family on a perpetual lease by the Mughal Emperor [[Shah Alam II]] in 1790. This grant was confirmed by the [[British Raj|British]] in 1807. Ajit Singh's family acquired Kuchesar Fort during the 18th century when the [[Najib ad-Dawlah]] bestowed the Jat family with the title of [[Rao Bahadur]] (Rai Bahadur).\nThe fort served as the erstwhile seat of Jat Kingdom of Uttar Pradesh. The fort is well-preserved and has been transformed into one of the most exotic heritage resorts in India.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Restoration and present-day operations==\nThe fort was restored and turned into a heritage-style hotel in 1994. The founding family still occupies a portion of the hotel, including the former reception area and [[Colonial India|colonial]]-style dining halls<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://worldarchitecture.org/architecture-projects/cphn/kuchesar_mud_fort_as_a_heritage_hotel-project-pages.html|title=Kuchesar Mud Fort, as a Heritage Hotel|website=worldarchitecture.org|language=en|access-date=2018-06-06}}</ref> with over 200 bedrooms. \n\nScenes from the 2017 Indian film [[The Hungry]], starring [[Naseeruddin Shah]] and [[Tisca Chopra]], were filmed at this location.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/entertainment/india-s-women-directors-make-a-mark-at-toronto-film-fest/story-M3YayfKigcFZ04steJu3JN.html|title=India\u2019s women directors make a mark at Toronto film fest|website=hindustantimes.com|language=en|access-date=2017-09-17}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n==External links ==\n\n* [http://www.mudfortkuchesar.com/ Kuchesar Fort, website]\n* {{Wikivoyage-inline|Kuchesar}}\n\n{{coord missing|Uttar Pradesh}}[https://www.google.com/maps/place/Kuchesar+Road+Chaupala,+Uttar+Pradesh+245201,+India/@28.7461979,77.9085697,15z/data=!3m1!4b1!4m5!3m4!1s0x390c827b3e85ba1d:0x4e07830dd899bfe5!8m2!3d28.7445054!4d77.91755 Google map location]\n\n{{Forts in India}}\n{{Forts in Uttar Pradesh}}\n\n[[Category:Forts in Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Heritage hotels in India]]\n[[Category:Bulandshahr district]]\n[[Category:18th-century establishments in India]]\n[[Category:18th-century forts in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2019}}\n\n'''Kuchesar (\u0915\u0941\u091a\u0947\u0938\u0930) Fort''', also known as the '''Mud Fort''', was built as an [[opium]] trading depot in India in 1734. Many '''royal heirs''' stayed in the Kuchesar Fort as a means of furthering profits stemming from India, thus increasing the trading depot's popularity. Eventually government officials closed the fort due to a significant number of [[Death|deaths]] and [[Disease|illnesses]]. Many theorized that a heap of overgrowing plants were responsible for the \"unhealthy environment\". Recently, the locals of [[Kuchesar]] took the initiative to clear away the plants that once grew all over the building. It was restored and is now known as \"Mud Hotel\" in the state of '''''[[Uttar Pradesh, India]],''''' and acts as a tourist attraction for the city. \n\n==History==\nKuchesar Fort was the seat of the Jat Princely estate at [[Kuchesar]]<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.historyfiles.co.uk/KingListsFarEast/IndiaJatsMinorKings.htm|title=Kingdoms of South Asia - Minor Indian Kingdoms of the Jats|website=www.historyfiles.co.uk|access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref> during the [[Mughal Empire]] and the [[British Raj]]. The [[Jat people]] competed with the [[Maratha]]s, the [[Rohilla|Rohillas,]] French colonists, traders and explorers, as well as the [[British East India Company]] after the decline of the [[Mughal Empire]]. Kuchesar Fort was also a center for the Rai Brahmins, also called Bhatts \u2013 a branch of [[Kashmiri Brahmins]]. They were the Rajkavi of Kuchesar State (Rajkavis are similar to [[Poet laureate|poets laureate]]). Rai Moti Bhatt was the last Rajkavi of the Kuchesar State.\n\nThe rulers of Kuchesar built the fort in 1734 and maintained state population and awareness records. The fort was granted to Ramdhan Singh's family on a perpetual lease by the Mughal Emperor [[Shah Alam II]] in 1790. This grant was confirmed by the [[British Raj|British]] in 1807. Ajit Singh's family acquired Kuchesar Fort during the 18th century when the [[Najib ad-Dawlah]] bestowed the Jat family with the title of [[Rao Bahadur]] (Rai Bahadur).\nThe fort served as the erstwhile seat of Jat Kingdom of Uttar Pradesh. The fort is well-preserved and has been transformed into one of the most exotic heritage resorts in India.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Restoration and present-day operations==\nThe fort was restored and turned into a heritage-style hotel in 1994. The founding family still occupies a portion of the hotel, including the former reception area and [[Colonial India|colonial]]-style dining halls<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://worldarchitecture.org/architecture-projects/cphn/kuchesar_mud_fort_as_a_heritage_hotel-project-pages.html|title=Kuchesar Mud Fort, as a Heritage Hotel|website=worldarchitecture.org|language=en|access-date=2018-06-06}}</ref> with over 200 bedrooms. \n\nScenes from the 2017 Indian film [[The Hungry]], starring [[Naseeruddin Shah]] and [[Tisca Chopra]], were filmed at this location.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/entertainment/india-s-women-directors-make-a-mark-at-toronto-film-fest/story-M3YayfKigcFZ04steJu3JN.html|title=India\u2019s women directors make a mark at Toronto film fest|website=hindustantimes.com|language=en|access-date=2017-09-17}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n==External links ==\n\n* [http://www.mudfortkuchesar.com/ Kuchesar Fort, website]\n* {{Wikivoyage-inline|Kuchesar}}\n\n{{coord missing|Uttar Pradesh}}[https://www.google.com/maps/place/Kuchesar+Road+Chaupala,+Uttar+Pradesh+245201,+India/@28.7461979,77.9085697,15z/data=!3m1!4b1!4m5!3m4!1s0x390c827b3e85ba1d:0x4e07830dd899bfe5!8m2!3d28.7445054!4d77.91755 Google map location]\n\n{{Forts in India}}\n{{Forts in Uttar Pradesh}}\n\n[[Category:Forts in Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Heritage hotels in India]]\n[[Category:Bulandshahr district]]\n[[Category:18th-century establishments in India]]\n[[Category:18th-century forts in India]]\n", "name_user": "Wasell", "label": "safe", "comment": "MOS:BOLD", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kuchesar_Fort"}
{"title_page": "Guntur", "text_new": "{{Use Indian English|date=June 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n<!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Indian cities]] for details -->\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Guntur\n| settlement_type                 = [[Metropolis]]\n| image_skyline                   = GunturCollage06022017.jpg\n| image_caption                   = Clockwise from Top Left: [[Guntur Medical College]], General Hospital, Iskon Temple, [[Guntur Municipal Corporation]], Chuttugunta Center, One-Town Center, A park with pond in Gujjanagundla.\n| etymology                       = Garthapuri (\"Place surrounded by water ponds\")\n| nickname                        = \n| pushpin_map                     = India Andhra Pradesh\n| pushpin_map_caption             = Location in Andhra Pradesh, India\n| pushpin_label                   = <!-- only necessary if \"name\" or \"official_name\" are too long -->\n| pushpin_label_position          = right\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|16.3008|N|80.4428|E|display=inline,title}}\n| coordinates_footnotes           = <!-- for references: use <ref>tags -->\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = [[India]]\n| subdivision_type1               = [[States and union territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Andhra Pradesh]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Guntur district|Guntur]]\n| established_title               = Founded\n| established_date                = 18th [[century]] [[Anno Domini|AD]]\n| founder                         = [[French people|French]]\n| established_title1              = Incorporated (town)\n| established_date1               = \n| established_title2              = Incorporated (city)\n| established_date2               = \n| named_for                       = <!-- seat, smaller parts -->\n| seat_type                       = <!-- defaults to: Seat -->\n| seat                            = [[Guntur Municipal Corporation]]\n| parts_type                      = Wards\n| parts                           = 58\n| government_footnotes            = <ref name=\"council\">{{cite news |last1=Reporter |first1=Staff |title=Now, parties gear up for polls to urban local bodies in Guntur |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/andhra-pradesh/now-parties-gear-up-for-polls-to-urban-local-bodies-in-guntur/article27097998.ece |accessdate=28 May 2019 |work=The Hindu |date=11 May 2019 |language=en-IN}}</ref>\n| government_type                 = [[Mayor\u2013council government|Mayor-council]]\n| governing_body                  = [[Guntur Municipal Corporation]]\n| leader_party                    = \n| leader_title                    = [[Mayor]]\n| leader_name                     = \n| leader_title1                   = [[Municipal Commissioner (India)|Municipal Commissioner]]\n| leader_name1                    = C Anuradha\n| leader_title2                   = [[Member of Legislative Assembly (India)|MLA{{'}}s]]\n| leader_name2                    = {{Collapsible list\n| title                           = List of MLAs\n| title_style                     = \n| frame_style                     = border:none; padding: 0;\n| list_style                      = text-align:left;display:none;\n| 1                               = Shaik Mohammad Musthafa <small>([[Guntur East (Assembly constituency)|East]])</small>\n| 2                               = Maddali Giridhara Rao <small>([[Guntur West (Assembly constituency)|West]])</small>\n}}\n| leader_title3                   = [[Member of Parliament|MP]]\n| leader_name3                    = [[Galla Jayadev]]\n| unit_pref                       = Metric\n| area_footnotes                  = <ref name=\"profile\">{{cite web |title=Municipality Profile |url=https://guntur.cdma.ap.gov.in/en/municipality-profile |website=Official website of Guntur Municipal Corporation |accessdate=28 May 2019}}</ref>\n| area_total_km2                  = 48.50\n| area_metro_footnotes            = <ref name=\"metro\">{{cite web|title=About Guntur Municipal Corporation|url=https://guntur.cdma.ap.gov.in/|website=Guntur Municipal Corporation|accessdate=30 May 2017}}</ref>\n| area_metro_km2                  = 159.46\n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = \n| population_as_of                = 2011\n| population_footnotes            = <ref name=\"census\">{{cite news|last1=Reporter|first1=Staff|title=Guntur city population is 743,354 as per 2011 Census|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/guntur-city-population-is-743354-as-per-2011-census/article4752495.ece|accessdate=13 February 2017|work=The Hindu}}</ref>\n| population                      = 743,354\n| pop_est_as_of                   = \n| pop_est_footnotes               = <ref name=\"est_pop\">{{cite news |last1=MN |first1=Samdani |title=Guntur: GMC\u2019s inter-city road infra project is aiding development on the outskirts |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/vijayawada/gmcs-inter-city-road-infra-project-is-aiding-development-on-the-outskirts/articleshow/63140988.cms |accessdate=28 May 2019 |work=The Times of India |date=3 March 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n| population_est                  = \n| population_rank                 = [[List of cities in Andhra Pradesh|3rd (in state)]]\n| population_density_km2          = auto\n| population_metro_footnotes      = \n| population_metro                = \n| population_blank1_title         = \n| population_blank1               = \n| population_demonym              = Gunturian,Gunturodu\n| population_note                 = <!-- demographics (section 1) -->\n| demographics_type1              = Literacy\n| demographics1_title1            = Literates\n| demographics1_info1             = \n| demographics1_title2            = Literacy rate\n| demographics1_info2             = \n| demographics_type2              = Languages\n| demographics2_title1            = Official\n| demographics2_info1             = [[Telugu language|Telugu]]\n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code                     = 522xxx\n| area_code_type                  = [[Telephone numbers in India|Telephone code]]\n| area_code                       = +91-863\n| registration_plate_type         = \n| registration_plate              = [[Vehicle registration plates of India|AP]]\n| website                         = {{URL|https://guntur.cdma.ap.gov.in/en}}\n| footnotes                       = \n| official_name                   = \n}}\n\n'''Guntur''' ({{audio|Guntur.ogg|pronunciation}}); is a city and the administrative headquarters of [[Guntur district]] in the [[States and territories of India|Indian state]] of [[Andhra Pradesh]].<ref name=\"census\" />{{rp|9}} Guntur city is the 24th most densely populated city in the world and 11th in India.<ref>http://www.deccanchronicle.com/nation/current-affairs/190816/vijayawada-is-third-densely-packed-city-31200-people-in-every-square-km.html</ref> It is situated {{convert|40|mi}} to the north of the [[Bay of Bengal]], on the [[Eastern Coastal Plains]]. The city forms a part of the [[Andhra Pradesh Capital Region]], administered by [[APCRDA]].<ref name=\"apcrda\">{{cite web |title=Declaration of A.P. Capital Region |url=https://crda.ap.gov.in/APCRDADOCS/DataModuleFIles/Maps/01~1324Zones-ULBs.jpg |website=[[Andhra Pradesh Capital Region Development Authority]] |publisher=[[Municipal Administration and Urban Development Department, Andhra Pradesh]] |accessdate=28 May 2019 |format=JPG |url-status=live |date=9 December 2014 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> It is a [[municipal corporation]] and also the headquarters of [[Guntur East mandal|Guntur East]] and [[Guntur West mandal]]s in [[Guntur revenue division]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehansindia.com/posts/index/Andhra-Pradesh/2018-03-31/Guntur-urban-divided-into-east-East-mandals/370772|title=Guntur urban divided into east, East mandals|last1=India|first1=The Hans|date=31 March 2018|work=thehansindia.com|accessdate=26 April 2019|location=Guntur}}</ref><ref name=\"map\">{{cite web|title=Guntur District Mandals |url=http://censusindia.gov.in/2011census/maps/atlas/28part32.pdf|publisher=Census of India|quote=It is also a good education based city... It has quality educational institutions also |accessdate=19 January 2015|pages=83,110}}</ref> {{As of|2011|}} [[census of India]] the city is the [[List of cities in Andhra Pradesh|third most populous]] in the state with a population of 743,354.<ref name=\"census\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Vijayawada/ap-capital-region-development-authority-comes-into-being/article6739396.ece|title = AP Capital Region Development Authority comes into being|date = 31 December 2014|access-date = 11 February 2015|newspaper = The Hindu|location = Hyderabad}}</ref> Guntur is classified as a ''Y-grade'' city as per the [[Pay Commission#Seventh Pay Commission|Seventh Central Pay Commission]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Classification of Cities for the purpose of HRA with effect from 1 April 2015 \u2014 CENTRAL GOVERNMENT EMPLOYEES NEWS|url=http://7thpaycommissionnews.in/classification-of-cities-for-the-purpose-of-hra-with-effect-from-1-4-2015/|website=7thpaycommissionnews.in|accessdate=1 July 2017}}</ref> It forms a part of Visakhapatnam-Guntur Industrial Region, a major industrial corridor in the country.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.yourarticlelibrary.com/industries/industrial-regions-8-major-industrial-regions-of-india/14159/ | title=Industrial Corridor | accessdate=16 May 2014}}</ref> The city is known for its chilli, cotton and tobacco exports and has the largest chilli market yard in [[Asia]].<ref name=\"largestchilliyard\">{{cite news|title=Chillies lose sting, exports & Guntur markets only hope \u2013 The Economic Times|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/commodities/chillies-lose-sting-exports-guntur-markets-only-hope/articleshow/2055828.cms?intenttarget=no|accessdate=27 May 2017|work=The Economic Times}}</ref>\n\n== Etymology ==\n\nThe earliest reference to the present name of the city can be dated back to the period of Ammaraja\u2013I (922-929 CE), the [[Vengi]] [[Eastern Chalukya]]n King. It also has its appearance in another two inscriptions dated 1147&nbsp;AD and 1158&nbsp;AD.<ref name=history>{{cite web|title=Guntur History|url=http://guntur.nic.in/history.html|publisher=National Informatics Centre|accessdate=27 July 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141008183724/http://guntur.nic.in/history.html|archive-date=8 October 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> In [[Sanskrit]], Guntur was referred to as ''Garthapuri''. \"Garthapuri\" or \"Guntlapuri\" translates to \"a place surrounded by water ponds\".<ref>{{cite web|title=District Profile|url=http://guntur.cdma.ap.gov.in/en/district-profile|website=Guntur Municipal Corporation|accessdate=6 June 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"scrprofile\">{{cite web|url=http://www.scr.indianrailways.gov.in/cris/uploads/files/1469081050829-aboutus-gen-18-7-16.pdf|title=Evolution of Guntur Division|last=|first=|date=|website=South Central Railway|publisher=|page=3|access-date=|accessdate=30 November 2015}}</ref> The settlement might have been near a pond, a \"gunta\" in Telugu; hence, :gunta uru\" translates to \"pond village\" in Telugu. Another source refers to \"kunta\" (a land measuring unit) which may have transformed to \"kunta uru\" and later to \"Guntur\".<ref>{{cite book|last1=Pullaiah|first1=T.|title=Flora of Guntur District, Andhra Pradesh, India|date=2000|publisher=Regency Publications|isbn=9788187498162|page=2|url=https://books.google.com/?id=1kHNgLyXbJUC&pg=PA2&lpg=PA2&dq=guntur+revenue+division+headquarters#v=onepage&q=guntur%20revenue%20division%20headquarters&f=false|accessdate=9 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n{{multiple image\n | width1 = 175\n | height1 = 250\n | image1 = Garthapuri2.jpg\n | alt1 = temple\n | width2 = 100\n | height2 = 50\n | image2 = Nagalipi1.jpg\n | alt2 = inscriptions\n | footer = Sivalayam at Old City and Inscriptions.\n}}\n\nThe earliest recorded reference of Guntur comes from the Idern plates of Ammaraja I (922\u2013929 CE), the Vengi [[Chalukya]]n king.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Gupta|first=Om|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eENU_a8c79MC&pg=PA853&lpg=PA853&dq=ammaraja+plates+guntur&source=bl&ots=7l1LTeIdAN&sig=ACfU3U3R5zN8haCFxpS3wrUXucQUTyeFYA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjfm5XiufDnAhXoQd8KHXg6CVYQ6AEwAHoECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=ammaraja%20plates%20guntur&f=false|title=Encyclopaedia of India, Pakistan and Bangladesh|date=April 2006|publisher=Gyan Publishing House|isbn=978-81-8205-389-2|language=en}}</ref> The inscriptions stones in the Agastyeshwara temple in 'Naga Lipi' (an ancient script) dates back to about 1100 [[Common Era|CE]]. It is located in Old Guntur and is considered one of the most famous temples in the city. It is said that [[Agastya]] built the temple in the last [[Treta Yuga]] around the [[swayambhu]] [[linga]] and hence it has this name. The 'Nagas' were said to have ruled the region at that time. R.Agraharam and Old Guntur areas are considered to be the older parts of the city.<ref>{{cite web |title=Temple inscriptions R.Agraharam|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/andhra-pradesh/2019/may/20/archaeologist-deciphers-gajapathi-period-guntur-temple-inscription-1979182.html|publisher=New Indian Express|accessdate=15 August 2019}}</ref> The region has been historically known for [[Buddhism]] and the first [[Kalachakra]] ceremony performed by [[Gautama Buddha]] himself.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kalacakra.org/history/khistor2.htm|title=K\u0101lacakra history|work=kalacakra.org}}</ref> The place of [[Sitanagaram]] and the [[Guttikonda Bilam|Guttikonda caves]] are referred in the ancient texts ([[Puranas|Vedic puranas]]) going back to the [[Treta Yuga]] and [[Dwapara Yuga]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://guntur.nic.in/history.html|title=:::- WELCOME TO GUNTUR DISTRICT OFFICIAL WEBSITE -:|publisher=|access-date=27 July 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141008183724/http://guntur.nic.in/history.html|archive-date=8 October 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> Old inscriptions of Satavahana period are found in Chebrolu area south of the city.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ancient Inscriptions|url=https://www.thehindu.com/sci-tech/science/earliest-sanskrit-inscription-in-south-india-found-in-ap/article30397972.ece|accessdate=30 December 2019|work=The Hindu|date=30 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nWith the arrival of the Europeans in the late sixteenth century the city attained national and international significance. The French shifted their headquarters from [[Kondavid Fort]] to here in 1752, probably because of the ample availability of water due to the two large tanks. This settlement formed the nucleus of the modern city. The [[Nizam|Nizams of Hyderabad]] and [[Hyder Ali]] also ruled the city until it came under [[British Raj|British rule]] in 1788. French astronomer, [[Pierre Janssen]] observed the [[solar eclipse]] of 18 August 1868 and discovered [[helium]], from Guntur in [[Madras State]], [[British India]].<ref>{{citation|last=Leggett|first=Hadley|title=Aug. 18, 1868: Helium Discovered During Total Solar Eclipse|date=18 August 2009|url=https://www.wired.com/2009/08/dayintech_0818/|publisher=wired.com|accessdate=18 March 2010}}</ref><ref>{{citation|title=Comptes rendus hebdomadaires des s\u00e9ances de l'Acad\u00e9mie des sciences|url=http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k3024c.image.r=comptes-rendus+hebdomadaires+Acad%C3%A9mie+des+Sciences.f836.langFR|journal=C. R. Acad. Sci. Paris|volume=67|pages=836\u201341|year=1868}}</ref> It was made the headquarters of a district named after it that was abolished in 1859, only to be reconstituted in 1904. The city rapidly became a major market for agricultural produce from the surrounding countryside due to the opening of the railway link in 1890. The expansion continued post independence as well and was concentrated in what is now called \"New Guntur\", with many urban areas such as [[Brodipet]], [[Arundelpet]] and suburban areas like Pattabhipuram, Chandramouli Nagar, Sita Rama nagar, Brindavan Gardens, etc.\n\nIn 2012, the city limits were expanded with the merger of surrounding ten villages, namely [[Nallapadu]], Pedapalakaluru, Ankireddipalem, Adavitakkellapadu, [[Gorantla, Guntur|Gorantla]], Pothuru, Chowdavaram, Etukuru, [[Budampadu]] and [[Reddypalem, Guntur|Reddypalem]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Merger of villages in Guntur city |url=http://www.gunturcorporation.org/townplanning/gos/GO_279_12072012.pdf |website=Guntur Municipal Corporation |publisher=Municipal Administration & Urban Development Department |accessdate=18 December 2018 }}</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\n[[File:NASA-GNT.jpg|right|thumb|Guntur Region from a satellite.]]\n\nGuntur is located at {{Coord|16.29|N|80.43|E|}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fallingrain.com/world/IN/02/Guntur.html|title=Falling Rain Genomics-Guntur|publisher=Falling Rain Genomics Inc.}}</ref> It has an average elevation of {{convert|33|m|ft|abbr=on}} and is situated on the plains. There are few hills in the surrounding suburban areas and Perecherla Reserve Forest on the north west. The city is around {{convert|40|mi|km}} to the west of the [[Bay of Bengal]] on the east coast of [[India]]. The [[Krishna River|Krishna]] delta lies partly in the [[Guntur district]]. There are other smaller rivers and channels in the region such as Guntur Channel, Chandravanka, Naagileru, Guntur Branch Canal<ref>{{cite web|url=http://irrigation.cgg.gov.in/dp/GunturDistrictProfile.jsp|title=Guntur irrigation|publisher=Government of India|access-date=12 October 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150716215306/http://irrigation.cgg.gov.in/dp/GunturDistrictProfile.jsp|archive-date=16 July 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> etc.\n\nAs quoted in NASA's website \"it is typical of the wider deltas along the southeast coast of India (known as the [[Coromandel Coast]]).<ref>{{cite web|title=KRISHNA R/DELTA, COAST|url=http://eol.jsc.nasa.gov/sseop/EFS/photoinfo.pl?PHOTO=STS032-72-61|website=Gateway to Astronaut Photography of Earth|accessdate=15 November 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714123236/http://eol.jsc.nasa.gov/sseop/EFS/photoinfo.pl?PHOTO=STS032-72-61|archivedate=14 July 2014}}</ref> The braided stream channels, broad floodplain, and extensive sandbars suggest that this part of the Krishna River flows through relatively flat terrain and carries a substantial amount of sediment, especially during the monsoon season.\"\n\n=== Climate ===\n\nAs per [[K\u00f6ppen-Geiger climate classification system]] the climate in Guntur is [[tropical climate|tropical]] (Aw). The average temperature is warm to hot year-round. The summer season (especially during May/June) has the highest temperatures, but these are usually followed by monsoon rains. The winter season (from November to February) is the most enjoyable with a pleasant climate. Winter months are usually dry, with little to no rainfall. The wettest month is July. The average annual temperature is 28.5 C and annual rain fall is about 905&nbsp;mm. Rain storms and cyclones are common in the region during the rainy season, which starts with the monsoons in early June. Cyclones may occur any time of the year, but occur more commonly between May and November.\n\n{{Weather box\n|width = auto\n|metric first=yes\n|single line=yes\n|location=Guntur City\n|Jan high C=29.8\n|Feb high C=32.2\n|Mar high C=34.7\n|Apr high C=36.8\n|May high C=39.3\n|Jun high C=37.5\n|Jul high C=33.3\n|Aug high C=32.9\n|Sep high C=32.8\n|Oct high C=31.7\n|Nov high C=30.3\n|Dec high C=29.2\n|Jan mean C=24.4\n|Feb mean C=26.2\n|Mar mean C=28.7\n|Apr mean C=31.4\n|May mean C=33.6\n|Jun mean C=32.6\n|Jul mean C=29.5\n|Aug mean C=29.2\n|Sep mean C=29.0\n|Oct mean C=28.0\n|Nov mean C=25.7\n|Dec mean C=24.1\n|Jan low C=19.0\n|Feb low C=20.3\n|Mar low C=22.8\n|Apr low C=25.8\n|May low C=28.0\n|Jun low C=27.7\n|Jul low C=25.7\n|Aug low C=25.5\n|Sep low C=25.3\n|Oct low C=24.2\n|Nov low C=21.1\n|Dec low C=19.0\n|precipitation colour=green\n|Jan precipitation mm=1\n|Feb precipitation mm=4\n|Mar precipitation mm=6\n|Apr precipitation mm=14\n|May precipitation mm=56\n|Jun precipitation mm=115\n|Jul precipitation mm=171\n|Aug precipitation mm=161\n|Sep precipitation mm=151\n|Oct precipitation mm=159\n|Nov precipitation mm=58\n|Dec precipitation mm=10\n|source 1= Climate-Data.org (altitude: 26&nbsp;m)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.climate-data.org/location/4945/ |title=Climate: Guntur \u2013 Climate graph, Temperature graph, Climate table |publisher=Climate-Data.org |accessdate=16 February 2016 }}</ref>\n}}\n\n== Demographics ==\n\n{{India census population\n|1981=367699\n|1991=471051\n|2001=514461\n|2011=670073\n|state=\n|title=Guntur population\n|footnote=Sources\n*(1981\u20132011):<ref name=\"ulb\" />}}\n\nIn the 1981 census, Guntur had a population of 367,699 with a growth rate of 36.19. {{As of|2011}} [[Census of India|census]], the city had a population of {{formatnum:670073}}.<ref name=\"ulb\" /> Later, it increased to {{formatnum:743354}} post merger of surrounding villages, which constitute {{formatnum:371727}} males and {{formatnum:371612}} females \u2014a sex ratio of 1004 females per 1000 males, higher than the national average of 940 females per 1000 males.<ref name=census /><ref>{{cite web |title=Sex Ratio|url=http://censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/indiaatglance.html|publisher=The Registrar General & Census Commissioner, India|accessdate=3 September 2014}}</ref> The 2018 estimate of the city population is estimated to be 8\u20139 [[lakh]].<ref name=\"est_pop\" />\n\n=== Language and religion ===\n\n{{bar box\n|title=Religion in Guntur (2011)\n|titlebar=#fcd666\n|float=right\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|Hinduism|orange|77.91}}\n{{bar percent|Islam|green|18.05}}\n{{bar percent|Christianity|red|3.25}}\n{{bar percent|Others (incl.unclassified and<br /> religion not stated)|grey|0.79}}\n}}\n\n[[Telugu language|Telugu]] is the widely spoken language with a total of {{formatnum:545928}} native speakers, followed by {{formatnum:109574}} [[Urdu]] speakers. A significant minority speak [[Hindi]], [[Odia language|Odia]] and [[Tamil language|Tamil]].<ref name=\"language\">{{cite web |title=C-16 Population By Mother Tongue \u2013 Town Level |url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/C-16_Town.html |website=[[Census of India]] |publisher=[[Registrar General and Census Commissioner of India]] |accessdate=13 May 2019}} ''Select \"Andhra Pradesh\" from the download menu. Data for \"Guntur (M+OG)\" is at row 12602 of the excel file.''</ref> The religious population constitute {{formatnum:522030}} [[Hindus]] (77.91%), {{formatnum:120974}} [[Muslims]] (18.05%), {{formatnum:21787}} [[Christians]] (3.25%), {{formatnum:2312}} [[Jains]] (0.35%) and {{formatnum:2605}} (0.82%) not stating any religion.<ref name=\"religion\">{{cite web |title=C-1 Population By Religious Community |url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/C-01.html |website=[[Census of India]] |publisher=[[Registrar General and Census Commissioner of India]] |accessdate=13 May 2019}} ''Select \"Andhra Pradesh\" from the download menu. Data for \"Guntur (M+OG)\" is at row 2682 of the excel file.''</ref> One of the purportedly lost tribes of [[Israel]] called [[Bene Ephraim]], has its presence in Guntur, with a Jewish synagogue as well.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Children of Ephraim: being Jewish in Andhra Pradesh|journal=Anthropology Today|volume=26 |url=https://www.academia.edu/1849132|accessdate=24 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Governance ==\n[[File:guntur-city-map.gif|thumb|right|City and neighborhood]]\n[[File:Guntur collectorate complex.jpg|thumb|right|The Collectorate complex of Guntur]]\n\n=== Civic administration and politics ===\n\nGuntur municipality is one of the oldest municipalities with more than 150 years of history.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jonathan |first1=P. Samuel |title=Guntur to get 24X7 water supply soon |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/andhra-pradesh/Guntur-to-get-24X7-water-supply-soon/article16083207.ece |accessdate=25 April 2019 |work=The Hindu |date=27 October 2016 |language=en-IN}}</ref> It was constituted with 25,000 population in 1866 and later got upgraded to third grade municipality in 1891, first grade in 1917, special grade in 1952 and then to selection grade in 1960. In 1994, it was finally made as [[municipal corporation]] and the first ever municipal election was conducted in 1995.<ref>{{cite web |title=TIMELINE !! |url=http://www.gunturcorporation.org/about_gmc/timeline.html |website=gunturcorporation.org |accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> In the year 2012, the city limits were expanded by merging ten surrounding villages into the [[Guntur Municipal Corporation]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Merger of gram panchayats in Guntur Municipal Corporation |url=http://www.gunturcorporation.org/townplanning/gos/GO_279_12072012.pdf |website=Guntur Municipal Corporation |publisher=Municipal Administration & Urban Development Department |accessdate=22 September 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131126163918/http://gunturcorporation.org/TownPlanning/gos/GO_279_12072012.pdf |archivedate=26 November 2013 }}</ref> There are a total 52 revenue wards in the corporation.<ref name=\"ulb\">{{cite web |title=Statistical Information of ULBs and UDAs |url=http://www.dtcp.ap.gov.in/dtcpweb/ulbs/List%20of%20ULBs-27-2-2019.pdf |website=Directorate of Town and Country Planning |publisher=Government of Andhra Pradesh |accessdate=29 May 2019 |page=3 |format=PDF |date=27 February 2019}}</ref> The present municipal [[commissioner]] is Shrikesh B Lathkar.<ref>{{cite news |last1=India |first1=The Hans |title=Shrikesh B Lathkar is new GMC chief |url=https://www.thehansindia.com/posts/index/Andhra-Pradesh/2018-03-17/Shrikesh-B-Lathkar-is-new-GMC-chief/367274 |accessdate=25 April 2019 |work=thehansindia.com |date=18 March 2018 |location=Guntur}}</ref> The corporation budget is {{INRConvert|973.24|c|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehansindia.com/posts/index/Andhra-Pradesh/2017-03-28/97324-cr-GMC-budget-passed-/289513|title=GMC budget|work=The HANS India | location=andhrapradesh|date=6 April 2017}}</ref> Recently the corporation topped the charts in property tax collections in the state.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/gmc-tops-charts-in-property-tax-collections/article17821240.ece|title=GMC tops charts in property tax collections|work=The Hindu | location=andhrapradesh, India|date=6 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Elections in India|Indian general elections]], [[Guntur (Lok Sabha constituency)|Guntur Lok Sabha constituency]] is one among the 25 constituencies in the state to represent the [[Lok Sabha]].<ref name=\"loksabha\">{{cite web|url=http://eci.nic.in/eci_main/CurrentElections/CONSOLIDATED_ORDER%20_ECI%20.pdf|title=Delimitation of Parliamentary and Assembly Constituencies Order, 2008|date=17 December 2018|website=The Election Commission of India|publisher=National Informatics Centre|page=31|format=PDF|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181003220916/http://eci.nic.in/eci_main/CurrentElections/CONSOLIDATED_ORDER%20_ECI%20.pdf|archive-date=3 October 2018|url-status=|access-date=25 April 2019}}</ref> While, [[Guntur East (Assembly constituency)|Guntur East]] and [[Guntur West (Assembly constituency)|Guntur West]] are the two assembly constituencies from 175 assembly segments, representing the state assembly.\n\n=== State offices ===\nAs part of the Andhra Pradesh capital region, the city hosts many state offices and agencies such as [[Andhra Pradesh Forest Department]], Agricultural Marketing Department etc.<ref name=\"departments\" />\n\n=== Utility services ===\n\n''Guntur Channel'' is the main source of drinking water for the city residents, which draws water from [[River Krishna]] through channels and tributaries.<ref>{{cite web |title=GUNTUR CHANNEL |url=https://irrigationap.cgg.gov.in/wrd/static/approjects/guntur_channel.html |website=irrigationap.cgg.gov.in |accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> Extension of this channel is being planned to cover more areas around the city in the capital region.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/andhra-pradesh/2018/may/29/guntur-channel-extension-survey-works-completed-1820791.html|title=Guntur Channel Extension|work=The Hindu|accessdate=30 May 2018|location=Guntur|date=30 May 2018}}</ref> Summer storage tank at [[Sangam Jagarlamudi]], Vengalayapalem reservoir are the other sources of water to the city.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Reporter |first1=Staff |title=Water crisis looms over Guntur |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/andhra-pradesh/Water-crisis-looms-over-Guntur/article14026329.ece |accessdate=25 April 2019 |work=The Hindu |date=29 January 2016 |location=Guntur |language=en-IN}}</ref> The [[Andhra Pradesh Southern Power Distribution Company Limited]] is responsible for power supply to the registered service connections through various sub-stations.<ref>{{cite news |title=Summer blues: Electricity demand reaches its peak |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/andhra-pradesh/2019/apr/20/summer-blues-electricity-demand-reaches-its-peak-1966532.html |accessdate=13 June 2019 |work=The New Indian Express |date=20 April 2019 |location=Guntur}}</ref> Guntur is one among the thirty-one cities in the state to be a part of water supply and sewerage services mission known as ''[[Atal Mission for Rejuvenation and Urban Transformation]] (AMRUT)''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Vadlapatla|first1=Sribala|title=Amaravati among 31 AP cities selected for Amruth development|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/hyderabad/Amaravati-among-31-AP-cities-selected-for-Amruth-development/articleshow/48431080.cms|accessdate=18 December 2015|work=The Times of India|date=11 August 2015|location=Hyderabad}}</ref> As per the 2018 Swachh Survekshan rankings, the city was ranked 129th in the country, with a score of 2460.18.<ref>{{cite web |title=Swachh Survekshan 2018 |url=http://swachhsurvekshan2018.org/Rankings/Morethan1Lakh |website=swachhsurvekshan2018.org |accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> The Guntur Municipal Corporation received the ''open defecation free city'' certificate as part of ''Swacch Bharat Mission''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Guntur is now officially \u2018Open Defecation-Free\u2019|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/nation/current-affairs/231216/guntur-is-now-officially-open-defaecation-free.html|accessdate=15 January 2017|work=deccanchronicle.com/|date=23 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Law and order ===\n\n[[File:Guntur District Court, India.jpg|thumb|left|City Court]]\n\nGuntur Urban and Rural police offices oversee the law and order for the city and the rural areas surrounding it.<ref name=\"hq\">{{cite news|title=Celebrations a big hit in Guntur|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/andhra-pradesh/celebrations-a-big-hit-in-guntur/article8758730.ece|accessdate=24 June 2016|work=The Hindu|date=22 June 2016}}</ref> The Guntur Urban Police is under consideration to be upgraded as Guntur Police Commissionerate.<ref>{{cite news|title=Guntur Police Commissionerate|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/andhra-pradesh/decks-cleared-for-guntur-police-commissionerate/article29728900.ece|accessdate=18 October 2019|work=The Hindu|date=18 October 2019}}</ref> The NCC Group Guntur is the National Cadet Corps of the Armed forces. It is located at Syamalanagar.<ref>{{cite web|title=NCC of Guntur|url=http://www.gunturncc.com|accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"hq\" /> The city also hosts one of the [[Indian Army]] recruitment and training centers.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/article1180122.ece|title=Army recruitment rally|work=The Hindu|accessdate=17 January 2008|location=Guntur|date=17 January 2008}}</ref> The city has a new Regional passport center to cater the citizens of the district and state.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/andhra-pradesh/passport-seva-kendra-opened/article23841999.ece|title=Passport Seva Kendra opened|work=The Hindu|accessdate=5 May 2018|location=Guntur|date=5 May 2018}}</ref>\nThe High Court was in Guntur after the separation from the erstwhile [[Madras State]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/2004/07/06/stories/2004070601210900.htm|title=Former High Court July 06, 1954|work=The Hindu | location=Chennai, India|date=6 July 2004}}</ref> which was later moved to [[Hyderabad]] after the formation of [[Andhra Pradesh]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/article3183383.ece|title=High Court bench requirement|work=The Hindu | location=Chennai, India|date=25 February 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/nation/current-affairs/100416/telangana-advocates-nudge-cji-on-hc-bifurcation.html|title=Telangana advocates nudge CJI on HC bifurcation|work=Deccan Chronicle| location=Hyderabad|date=10 April 2016}}</ref> After the bifurcation of the state a new High Court is setup in the capital region of the district.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/visakhapatnam/andhra-pradesh-high-court-returns-home-to-guntur-after-62-years/articleshow/67278307.cms\n|title=New High Court|work=Times of India| location=Visakhapatnam|date=31 December 2018}}</ref> The AP State Judicial Preview offices are located at Nagarampalem.<ref>{{cite web|title=AP Judicial Preview|url=http://www.judicialpreview.ap.gov.in|website=judicialpreview.ap.gov.in|accessdate=24 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Guntur-government-hospital-traumacare.jpg|thumb|A trauma care center in Guntur]]\n\n=== Healthcare ===\nThe Government General Hospital provides free health care to people across the district.<ref>{{cite news|title=Government General Hospital becomes clean|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/151222/nation-current-affairs/article/government-general-hospital-becomes-clean|accessdate=24 May 2017|work=Deccan Chronicle|date=22 December 2015}}</ref> There are free healthcare facilities like [[Sankara Eye Hospital]] that serves people in and around the city. Also there are urban health care centers, couple of hundred private hospitals in the city.<ref>{{cite news|title=Guntur analysis report|url=http://guntur.cdma.ap.gov.in/sites/default/files/City%20Sanitation-Plan%20.pdf|accessdate=13 June 2018|work=guntur.cdma.ap.gov.in|date=June 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Economy ==\n[[File:Guntur vegetable market.jpg|thumb|right|Main market]]\n\nThe city is headquarters to ''Agricultural Marketing Department''.<ref name=\"departments\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/andhra-pradesh/guntur-will-be-hq-of-agri-department-minister/article8734456.ece|title=Departments moving to new Capital Region|work=The Hindu|date=16 June 2016}}</ref> ''The Tobacco Board'', ''The Spices Board'' also has their headquarters located in the city.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Goswami |first1=Bhupen |title=Bengal Opposes Tea Board of India headquarter shift To Assam |url=https://www.apnnews.com/bengal-opposes-tea-board-of-india-headquarter-shift-to-assam/ |accessdate=25 April 2019 |work=APN News |date=8 October 2018 |location=Guwahati}}</ref> ''Agriculture Market Committee Market Yard'', the largest chilly yard of [[Asia]], generates an income of up to {{INRConvert|100|c|abbr=on}} during trading season.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jonathan|first1=P. Samuel|title=Trading at Guntur chilli marketyard comes to a halt|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/andhra-pradesh/trading-at-guntur-chilli-yard-comes-to-a-halt/article8365792.ece|accessdate=27 May 2017|work=The Hindu}}</ref><ref name=\"largestchilliyard\" /> The spiciest Guntur chillies are exported to foreign countries and the city stands second in terms of trade, next to [[Mexico]].<ref name=\"chillies\">{{cite web|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/magazine/story/hai-hai-mirchi/233612|title= Guntur Chillies|work=Online edition of Outlook magazine-free registration required|accessdate=1 August 2007}}</ref> Commercial activities are concentrated mostly on outlets such as, cinema halls, malls, jewelry, fertilisers.<ref name=\"chillies\" /> There are also several spinning mills on the outskirts of the city.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jonathan |first1=P. Samuel |title=Highway connectivity set to improve in Guntur |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/andhra-pradesh/highway-connectivity-set-to-improve-in-guntur/article25809979.ece |accessdate=25 April 2019 |work=The Hindu |date=23 December 2018 |language=en-IN}}</ref>\n\n== Culture ==\n\nThe city residents are referred as ''Gunturians''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Braving chill, Gunturians walk with enthusiasm|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/andhra-pradesh/braving-chill-gunturians-walk-with-enthusiasm/article8150419.ece|accessdate=3 March 2016|work=The Hindu|date=25 January 2016|location=Guntur}}</ref> Traditional drama and theatrical events also have their presence in the city.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/article3086666.ece|title=Folk art fete in Guntur |work=The Hindu |location=Chennai, India|date=7 August 2006}}</ref> The city observes many festivals such as [[Rama Navami]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Rama Navami festival in Guntur|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Vijayawada/srirama-navami-celebrated-on-a-grand-scale/article4636700.ece|accessdate=16 October 2017|work=The Hindu}}</ref> [[Maha Shivaratri|Maha Sivaratri]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Guntur: Maha Shivarathri festival|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/nation/current-affairs/250217/guntur-mahashivratri-fervour-everywhere.html|accessdate=17 November 2017|work=Deccan Chronicle}}</ref> [[Ganesh Chaturthi|Vinayaka Chavithi]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Vinayaka Chavithi festivities in Guntur|url=http://www.thehansindia.com/posts/index/Hans/2015-09-17/Vinayaka-Chavithi-festivities-in-Guntur/176332|accessdate=17 November 2017|work=The Hans India}}</ref> [[Navaratri|Vijaya Dasami]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Navaratri in Guntur|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/temples-decked-up-for-navaratri-festivities-in-guntur/article5206200.ece|accessdate=11 November 2017|work=The Hindu}}</ref> [[Deepawali]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Diwali celebrated with gaiety in AP, Telangana|url=http://www.thehansindia.com/posts/index/Telangana/2015-11-12/Diwali-celebrated-with-gaiety-in-AP-Telangana/186016|accessdate=4 October 2016|work=The Hans India}}</ref> [[Holi]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Gaiety, colour, fervour mark Holi festivities|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Vijayawada/gaiety-colour-fervour-mark-holi-festivities/article8390879.ece|accessdate=4 October 2016|work=The Hindu|date=24 March 2016}}</ref> [[Ugadi]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Sahiti Vasanthotsavam on Ugadi|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/sahiti-vasanthotsavam-on-ugadi/article4597499.ece|accessdate=22 November 2017|work=The Hindu|date=9 April 2013}}</ref> [[Eid al-Adha|Eid]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Nation Celebrates Eid-ul-Adha with Religious Fervour|url=http://www.sakshipost.com/news/2016/09/13/nation-celebrates-eid-ul-adha-with-religious-fervour|accessdate=4 October 2016|work=Sakshipost|date=13 September 2016}}</ref> [[Krishnastami]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Gaiety, fervour mark Krishna Janmashtami|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/andhra-pradesh/2017/aug/15/gaiety-fervour-mark-krishna-janmashtami-1643356.html|accessdate=11 November 2017|work=New Indian Express}}</ref> [[Christmas]].<ref>{{cite news|title=CM Chandrababu for Guntur today|url=http://www.thehansindia.com/posts/index/Andhra-Pradesh/2014-12-24/CM-Chandrababu-for-Guntur-today/122666|accessdate=4 October 2016|work=The Hans India}}</ref>\n\n=== Cuisine ===\n\nThe [[South Indian]] breakfast varieties such as, [[Idli]], [[Dosa]], [[Puri]], [[Vada (food)|Vada]] etc., are preferred mostly.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ganguly|first1=Nivedita|title=A delightful dosa fare|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/Food/foods-express-a-delightful-dosa-fare/article8566203.ece|accessdate=4 October 2016|work=The Hindu|date=6 May 2016}}</ref> The ''Red chilli biryani'' is one of the native dish from the area.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ganguly|first1=Nivedita|title=Traditional flavours of Andhra|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/Food/traditional-flavours-of-andhra/article7259701.ece|accessdate=4 October 2016|work=The Hindu|date=29 May 2015}}</ref> [[Guntur Sannam]], a [[Chili pepper|chilli]] variety was registered as one of the geographical indication from Andhra Pradesh under the ''Geographical Indications of Goods (Registration and Protection) Act, 1999''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Geographical Indication|url=http://www.thehansindia.com/posts/index/News-Analysis/2016-01-23/Geographical-Indication/201919|accessdate=4 October 2016|work=The Hans India}}</ref>\n\n=== Cityscape ===\n{{Panorama|image = File:Panoramic view of Guntur.JPG|height = 275|alt = |caption = A residential area}}\n[[File:Baudha Sree Archaeological Museum in Guntur.jpg|thumb|right|Archaeological Museum]]\n\nThe major commercial and residential areas in the city include the Arundelpet, Lakshmipuram and Brodipet. Koretapadu, Navabharath Nagar, Pattabhipuram, Shyamla Nagar and Vidya Nagar etc., are some of the other areas in the city.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Samuel Jonathan|first1=P|title=Guntur looking skyward|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Vijayawada/guntur-looking-skyward/article6242690.ece|accessdate=28 February 2016|work=The Hans India|date=24 July 2014|location=Vijayawada}}</ref> Autonagar, Gorantla, Peda Palakaluru, Nallapadu, Chennai to Kolkata Highway etc. are some of the other areas of the city.<ref>{{cite news|title=Guntur Inner Ring Road Inaugurated by Kiran|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/andhra_pradesh/Guntur-Inner-Ring-Road-Inaugurated-by-Kiran/2014/02/17/article2060940.ece|accessdate=3 March 2016|work=The New Indian Express|date=17 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe city has many parks, museums, temples, nature conservation sites, forts, resorts and caves. The [[Jinnah Tower]] is one of the iconic structure on Mahatma Gandhi Road, one of the important center of the city.<ref>{{cite news|title=Blog: Finding Kamala Nehru in Pakistan, Jinnah in Guntur|url=http://www.ndtv.com/blog/finding-kamala-nehru-in-pakistan-jinnah-in-guntur-764557|accessdate=23 September 2016|work=NDTV|date=20 May 2015}}</ref> There are seventeen parks in the city with some of them maintained by the municipal corporation.<ref>{{cite web|title=Other parks in Guntur city !!|url=http://www.gunturcorporation.org/about_gmc/other_parks.html|website=Guntur Municipal Corporation|accessdate=23 September 2016}}</ref>\nLarger city parks like Nagara-Vanam are being developed on the outskirts of the city.<ref>{{cite news|title=Nagara Vanam Park at Guntur|url=http://www.uniindia.com/cm-inaugurates-nagara-vanam-park-at-guntur/states/news/1037130.html|accessdate=14 November 2017|work=United News India|date=14 November 2017}}</ref> There are many places to visit near by the city such as [[Uppalapadu Bird Sanctuary]], [[Kondaveedu Fort]] etc. There are many festivals and events in the region such as beach festivals, hill festivals attract the city residents during various festival seasons. The closest beach to the city region is [[Suryalanka Beach|Surya Lanka]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Beach festival|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/andhra-pradesh/2019/dec/30/surya-lanka-beach-festival-on-january-11-12-2082683.html|accessdate=30 December 2019|work=New Indian Express|date=30 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Beach festival, Guntur|url=https://www.ap.gov.in/?p=42019|accessdate=30 December 2019|work=AP State Portal|date=30 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Hill festival Kondaveedu|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Vijayawada/kondaveedu-hill-festival-from-today/article26285046.ece|accessdate=30 December 2019|work=The Hindu|date=30 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Hill festival|url=https://www.thehansindia.com/posts/index/Andhra-Pradesh/2019-01-11/Kotappakonda-fest-to-promote-eco-awareness/473270|accessdate=30 December 2019|work=The Hans India|date=30 December 2019}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n== Transport ==\n[[File:NTR Bus Station Bepartye Block.jpg|thumb|[[NTR bus station|NTR Bus Station]]]]\n[[File:Guntur Junction railway station in 2007.jpg|thumb|left|Guntur railway station]]\n[[File:Rps20160709 141628.jpg|thumb|right|National Highway-16 near [[Namburu]]]]\n\nThe local transport preferred by the commuters include, privately operated [[auto rickshaw]]s, cabs, mini-buses etc., and government run [[APSRTC]] buses in specified routes.<ref name=\"localtransport\">{{cite news|title=Private operators eat into APSRTC\u2019s income|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/nation/current-affairs/250217/private-operators-eat-into-apsrtcs-income.html|accessdate=24 May 2017|work=Deccan Chronicle|date=25 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/andhra-pradesh/2016/aug/17/Auto-rickshaw-drivers-charge-double-fare-1510037.html|title=Auto-rickshaw drivers charge double fare|work=The New Indian Express|accessdate=24 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/andhra-pradesh/new-fleet-of-city-buses-in-guntur/article7560407.ece|title=New fleet of city buses in Guntur|last1=Reporter|first1=Staff|date=20 August 2015|work=The Hindu|accessdate=24 May 2017}}</ref> Everyday, close to one [[lakh]] people travel by different modes of transport.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/andhra-pradesh/2018/mar/29/mini-bus-station-at-guntur-to-help-ease-traffic-congestion-1794185.html|title=Mini bus station at Guntur to help ease traffic congestion|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2019-05-21}}</ref> [[Auto rickshaw]]s operating on a sharing basis are the cheapest form of transport for the students and the working population.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/andhra-pradesh/new-fleet-of-city-buses-in-guntur/article7560407.ece|title=New fleet of city buses in Guntur|last=Reporter|first=Staff|date=2015-08-20|work=The Hindu|access-date=2019-05-21|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> [[NTR bus station]] handles more than 2000 buses everyday, which arrive from different districts of the state.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/nation/current-affairs/290318/mini-bus-station-to-come-up-in-guntur-in-2-weeks.html|title=Mini bus station to come up in Guntur in 2 weeks|date=2018-03-29|website=Deccan Chronicle|language=en|access-date=2019-05-21}}</ref> A new mini bus station is being built in the premises of the present one, to run city and non stop services.<ref name=\":0\" /> The ''Rail Vikas Bhavan'' at Pattabhipuram in the city is the headquarters of [[Guntur railway division]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Guntur Division|url=http://gunturdivision.blogspot.in/|website=gunturdivision.blogspot.in|accessdate=4 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/news/jul/04ap.htm|title=Rediff On The NeT: Paswan to inaugurate new railway division at Guntur|publisher=}}</ref> {{rws|Guntur Junction}}, {{rws|Nallapadu}} and {{rws|New Guntur}} railway stations of the city provide rail transport.<ref name=\"rail\">{{cite news|title=Connected Guntur will spur growth|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/151221/nation-current-affairs/article/connected-guntur-will-spur-growth|accessdate=4 June 2016|work=Deccan Chronicle|date=21 December 2015}}</ref> While, {{rws|Namburu}}, [[Perecherla]] and {{rws|Pedakakani Halt}} railway stations serve as satellite stations to the city commuters.<ref>{{cite news|title=Guntur misses metro rail project|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/140922/nation-current-affairs/article/capital-talk-guntur-misses-metro-rail-project|accessdate=28 August 2016|work=Deccan Chronicle|date=22 September 2014}}</ref> The Guntur railway station operates [[MEMU]] and local trains for the commuting population, including thousands of university students.<ref>{{cite news|title=Guntur misses metro rail project|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/140922/nation-current-affairs/article/capital-talk-guntur-misses-metro-rail-project|accessdate=24 May 2017|work=Deccan Chronicle|date=22 September 2014}}</ref> Though there was a proposal to build a [[no frills]] airport for the city,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Reddy|first1=B. Dasarath|title=Traffic rise in old airports gives a boost to Andhra's plan to build 6 new runways|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/economy-policy/traffic-rise-in-old-airports-gives-a-boost-to-andhra-s-plan-to-build-6-new-runways-115122200787_1.html|accessdate=24 May 2017|work=Business Standard India|date=25 December 2015}}</ref> the [[Vijayawada International Airport]] located at [[Gannavaram]] serves the air travel needs of the city commuters.<ref name=Businessline>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/national/gannavaram-airport-named-after-amaravati/article9475939.ece|title=Gannavaram Airport to be named as Amaravati airport|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|access-date=12 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe city has a total road length of {{Convert|893.00|km|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=Details of Roads in each ULB of Andhra Pradesh|url=http://centralapp.cdma.ap.gov.in:8080/CDMAAPTaxesInfo/RoadDetails.jsp|website=Municipal Administration and Urban Development Department|accessdate=27 June 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160801101300/http://centralapp.cdma.ap.gov.in:8080/CDMAAPTaxesInfo/RoadDetails.jsp|archivedate=1 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The [[Inner Ring Road, Guntur|Mahatma Gandhi Inner Ring Road]] is an arterial road with a stretch of {{convert|6.34|km|mi|abbr=on}}, that encircles the city with its start and end points on [[National Highway 16 (India)|NH 16]].<ref>{{cite news|title=AP CM inaugurates phase I & II of Guntur inner ring road|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/ap-cm-inaugurates-phase-i-ii-of-guntur-inner-ring-road-114021600601_1.html|accessdate=3 March 2016|work=Business Standard|date=16 February 2014|location=Hyderabad}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Guntur Inner Ring Road Inaugurated by Kiran|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/andhra_pradesh/Guntur-Inner-Ring-Road-Inaugurated-by-Kiran/2014/02/17/article2060940.ece|accessdate=4 June 2016|work=The New Indian Express|date=17 February 2014}}</ref> The other arterial city roads include, the ''Grand Trunk Road'', ''JKC College Road'', ''Lakshmipuram Road'', ''Pattabhipuram Road'' and ''Palakaluru Road'' etc.<ref>{{cite news|title=One-stop destination for pilgrims|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/andhra-pradesh/onestop-destination-for-pilgrims/article8602162.ece|accessdate=25 June 2016|work=The Hindu|date=15 May 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"apsrtc\">{{cite news|title=New fleet of city buses in Guntur|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/andhra-pradesh/new-fleet-of-city-buses-in-guntur/article7560407.ece|accessdate=16 February 2016|work=The Hindu|date=20 August 2015|location=Guntur}}</ref> The city is connected to major destinations by [[National Highway (India)|National highways]], [[State highways]] and district roads.<ref>{{cite web|title=3.4 Infrastructure|url=http://www.gunturcorporation.org/Adminx/Development_Plan.pdf|website=Guntur Municipal Corporation|accessdate=24 May 2017|page=19}}</ref> [[National Highway 16 (India)|National Highway 16]] bypasses the city, which is also a part of [[Asian Highway 45]] and [[Golden Quadrilateral]].<ref>{{cite news|title=NHAI Under Pressure to Lay Another Bypass Road|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/andhra_pradesh/NHAI-Under-Pressure-to-Lay-Another-Bypass-Road/2014/08/25/article2397230.ece|accessdate=4 June 2016|work=The New Indian Express|date=25 August 2014}}</ref> The [[State Highway 2 (Andhra Pradesh)|State Highway 2]] connects the city with [[Macherla]] and [[Hyderabad]]. A new [[Amaravati\u2013Anantapur Expressway|Expressway]] is proposed connecting the city to [[Rayalaseema]] region with faster access. [[State Highway 48 (Andhra Pradesh)|State Highway 48]] with [[Bapatla]] and [[Chirala]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Samuel Jonathan|first1=P|title=Nizampatnam backwaters beckon adventure geeks|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/andhra-pradesh/nizampatnam-backwaters-beckon-adventure-geeks/article7736196.ece|accessdate=29 February 2016|work=The Hindu|date=8 October 2015|location=Guntur}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Road Maps|url=http://aproads.cgg.gov.in/getInfo.do|website=Roads and Buildings Department|publisher=Government of Andhra Pradesh|accessdate=29 February 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160223164436/http://aproads.cgg.gov.in/getInfo.do|archivedate=23 February 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The ''Guntur\u2013Amaravati,''<ref>{{cite news|title=Guntur hogs limelight, bags two Central institutes|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/andhra-pradesh/guntur-hogs-limelight-bags-two-central-institutes/article8013427.ece|accessdate=25 June 2016|work=The Hindu|date=21 December 2015}}</ref> ''Guntur\u2013 Nandivelugu'' ,''Guntur-Tenali''.<ref>{{cite news|title=It's rain's turn to torment Guntur|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/andhra_pradesh/Its-rains-turn-to-torment-Guntur/2016/06/11/article3476407.ece|accessdate=25 June 2016|work=The New Indian Express|date=11 June 2016}}</ref> and ''Guntur-Parchoor'' roads<ref>{{cite web|title=:: APRDC|url=http://aprdc.ap.gov.in/UI/Profile.aspx|website=Andhra Pradesh Road Development Corporation|publisher=Roads and Buildings Department|accessdate=9 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161109221321/http://aprdc.ap.gov.in/UI/Profile.aspx|archive-date=9 November 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Rathaiah\u2019s biography launched|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Vijayawada/rathaiahs-biography-launched/article6258366.ece|accessdate=25 June 2016|work=The Hindu|date=29 July 2014}}</ref> are the district roads connecting their respective destinations.\n\n== Education and research ==\n[[File:Guntur-Agri-University.jpg|thumb|right|A university campus]]\n\nThe primary and secondary school education is imparted by government, aided and private schools, under the ''School Education Department'' of the state.<ref>{{cite web|title=School Education Department|url=http://rmsaap.nic.in/Notification_TSG_2015.pdf|publisher=School Education Department, Government of Andhra Pradesh|accessdate=12 April 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160319051231/http://rmsaap.nic.in/Notification_TSG_2015.pdf|archivedate=19 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Department of School Education \u2013 Official AP State Government Portal {{!}} AP State Portal |url=http://www.ap.gov.in/department/organizations/school-education/ |website=ap.gov.in |accessdate=7 November 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161107155331/http://www.ap.gov.in/department/organizations/school-education/ |archivedate= 7 November 2016 }}</ref> As per the school information report for the academic year 2015\u201316, the city limits (including the merged villages) have more than one lakh students enrolled in over 400 schools.<ref>{{cite web|title=School Information Report|url=http://cse.ap.gov.in/DSE/totalSchoolReport.xls#|website=Commissionerate of School Education|publisher=Government of Andhra Pradesh|accessdate=8 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161108154343/http://cse.ap.gov.in/DSE/totalSchoolReport.xls|archive-date=8 November 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Student Information Report|url=http://cse.ap.gov.in/DSE/districtStudentReport.do?mode=getVillageReportsList&mandalCode=281726&mandalName=GUNTUR|website=Commissionerate of School Education|publisher=Child info 2015\u201316, District School Education \u2013 Andhra Pradesh|accessdate=8 November 2016}}</ref> The [[Central Board of Secondary Education]], [[Secondary School Certificate]] or the [[Indian Certificate of Secondary Education]] are the different types of syllabus followed by different schools. The medium of instruction followed by schools are English, Telugu and Urdu.<ref name=\"municipal_schools\">{{cite news|title=74 GMC schools switch to English medium \u2013 Times of India|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/vijayawada/74-GMC-schools-switch-to-English-medium/articleshow/53203336.cms|accessdate=23 September 2016|work=The Times of India}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Mallikarjun|first1=Y.|title=Classrooms in State-run schools set to go digital|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/andhra-pradesh/classrooms-in-staterun-schools-set-to-go-digital/article8293878.ece|accessdate=23 September 2016|work=The Hindu|date=29 February 2016}}</ref> The public library system is supported by the government with the central library located at Arundalpet.<ref>{{cite web|title=Public Libraries in Guntur|url=http://publiclibraries.ap.nic.in/distwise/guntur.html|accessdate=31 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nGovernment colleges and institutions include, [[Guntur Medical College]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Reporter|first1=Staff|title=MCI team inspects Guntur Medical College|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/andhra-pradesh/mci-team-inspects-guntur-medical-college/article8246146.ece|accessdate=27 September 2016|work=The Hindu|date=17 February 2016}}</ref> Government Junior College for Girls.<ref name=\"colleges\">{{cite web|title=List of colleges in Guntur district|url=http://bieap.gov.in/pdf/guntur.pdf|website=Board of Intermediate Education|accessdate=27 September 2016}}</ref> There exists one residential college under APRJC, ten private aided, two co-operative and many private unaided colleges.<ref name=\"colleges\" /> [[Hindu College (Guntur)|Hindu College]], [[Andhra Christian College|A.C College]] are some of the older institutes in the city. [[Jagarlamudi Kuppuswamy Chowdary College|JKC College]], [[RVR & JC College of Engineering]], Tellakula Jalayya Polisetty Somasundaram College (TJPS College), Government College for Women and St. Joseph's College of Education for Women are the autonomous colleges approved under Universities Grant Commission scheme.<ref>{{cite web|title=Autonomous colleges list|url=http://www.ugc.ac.in/oldpdf/colleges/autonomous_colleges-list.pdf|website=Universities Grants Commission|accessdate=27 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018071151/http://www.ugc.ac.in/oldpdf/colleges/autonomous_colleges-list.pdf|archive-date=18 October 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> The [[Acharya N. G. Ranga Agricultural University]] at [[Lam, Guntur district|Lam village]] near the city is administered from Gorantla area of the city.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Reporter|first1=Staff|title=Marketing Department moves to capital region|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/andhra-pradesh/marketing-department-moves-to-capital-region/article8726899.ece|accessdate=27 September 2016|work=The Hindu|date=14 June 2016}}</ref> Research centres related to different fields such as, Regional [[AGMARK]] laboratory,<ref>{{cite web|title=Information on Right to Information Act, 2005 Pertaining to Directorate of Marketing & Inspection|url=http://www.agmarknet.nic.in/right_info2.htm#Rules,%20Regulations,%20instructions,%20manuals%20and%20records%20held%20by%20it%20or|website=Agricultural Marketing|accessdate=4 October 2016}}</ref> regional station of ''Central Tobacco Research Institute'' of [[Indian Council of Agricultural Research]] are also present.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bureau|first1=Our|title=Tobacco Board sets export target at Rs 10,000 cr|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/economy/agri-business/tobacco-board-sets-export-target-at-rs-10000-cr/article6435505.ece|accessdate=4 October 2016|work=The Hindu Business Line|date=22 September 2014}}</ref> The city hosts many national, state level conferences and expos on many topics like economy, agriculture, technology etc.<ref>{{cite web|title=National conferences, Guntur|url=http://nationalconferences.org/conference.php?dt=2018-01-21&place=Guntur,%20India|accessdate=28 December 2017|work=nationalconferences.org|date=28 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Bureau|first1=Our|title=President inaugurates IEA conference in Guntur|url=http://www.merinews.com/article/president-kovind-inaugurates-the-centenary-conference-of-the-indian-economic-association-in-guntur/15928456.shtml|accessdate=28 December 2017|work=Merinews|date=27 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Bureau|first1=Our|title=Pharmacy expo, Guntur|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/pharmacy-expo-draws-students/article20834746.ece|accessdate=28 December 2017|work=The Hindu|date=25 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Bureau|first1=Our|title=Tech expo in Guntur|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/andhra-pradesh/2017/dec/04/vignan-varsity-hosts-tech-expo-1717828.html|accessdate=28 December 2017|work=New Indian Express|date=4 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Media ==\n\nAs per the 58th annual report of Press India 2013\u201314, the major Telugu daily publications from Guntur are [[ABN Andhra Jyothi|Andhra Jyothi]], [[Eenadu]], [[Andhra Prabha]], [[Sakshi (newspaper)|Sakshi]], [[Suryaa (newspaper)|Suryaa]], [[Vaartha|Telugu Jatiya Dinapatrika Vaartha]]. The English publications are, [[Deccan Chronicle]], News Boom, The Fourth Voice, Views Observer.<ref name=\"newspapers\">{{cite web|title=Press in India, 2013\u201314|url=http://rni.nic.in/pin1314.pdf|website=The Registrar of Newspapers for India|accessdate=5 June 2017|pages=358\u2013403|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170623020046/http://www.rni.nic.in/pin1314.pdf|archive-date=23 June 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Sports ==\n[[File:Guntur parade ground.jpg|thumb|right|Parade ground]]\n\nSporting infrastructure of the city include several venues for many sports such as, Brahmananda Reddy stadium for [[Tennis]], [[Badminton]], [[Volleyball]], Athletics, [[Gymnastics]], [[Swimming (sport)|Swimming]];<ref>{{cite news|last1=Reporter|first1=Staff|title=Nod for swimming pool at BR stadium in Guntur|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/andhra-pradesh/nod-for-swimming-pool-at-br-stadium-in-guntur/article4797193.ece|accessdate=29 September 2016|work=The Hindu|date=9 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Jonathan|first1=P. Samuel|title=Kids learn the basics of tennis|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/andhra-pradesh/kids-learn-the-basics-of-tennis/article8648369.ece|accessdate=29 September 2016|work=The Hindu|date=26 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Guntur athletic trials|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-sports/guntur-athletic-trials/article7634817.ece|accessdate=29 September 2016|work=The Hindu|date=10 September 2015}}</ref> NTR Municipal Indoor stadium for [[Table Tennis]] and [[Volleyball]];<ref>{{cite news|title=Place for TT at NTR indoor stadium|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Vijayawada/place-for-tt-at-ntr-indoor-stadium/article8858199.ece|accessdate=29 September 2016|work=The Hindu|date=16 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"The Hindu\">{{cite news|last1=Reporter|first1=Staff|title=Volleyball tournament off to a smashing start in Guntur|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/andhra-pradesh/volleyball-tournament-off-to-a-smashing-start-in-guntur/article8278892.ece|accessdate=29 September 2016|work=The Hindu|date=25 February 2016}}</ref> and also other sports such as [[Boxing]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Reporter|first1=Staff|title=Young boxers from Guntur district win laurels|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Vijayawada/young-boxers-from-guntur-district-win-laurels/article6571119.ece|accessdate=29 September 2016|work=The Hindu|date=6 November 2014}}</ref>\nIt becomes the first state to get blue athletic track in India <ref>https://www.deccanchronicle.com/sports/in-other-news/040117/guntur-becomes-the-first-state-to-get-blue-athletics-track.html</ref>\n\nThe city has hosted sporting events such as, ''All India Senior Tennis Association'',<ref>{{cite news|last1=Reporter|first1=Staff|title=AISTA tennis tourney gets under way|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/aista-tennis-tourney-gets-under-way/article8176872.ece|accessdate=29 September 2016|work=The Hindu|date=1 February 2016}}</ref> ''All India Sub Junior Ranking Badminton Tournament'',<ref>{{cite news|last1=Reporter|first1=Staff|title=Badminton tourney gets under way|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/andhra-pradesh/badminton-tourney-gets-under-way/article7781956.ece|accessdate=29 September 2016|work=The Hindu|date=20 October 2015}}</ref> ''All India Invitation Volleyball Tournament'',<ref name=\"The Hindu\" /> ''Ganta Sanjeeva Reddy Memorial Trophy'',<ref>{{cite news|title=Swimming championships from July 10 \u2013 Times of India|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/hyderabad/Swimming-championships-from-July-10/articleshow/52912438.cms|accessdate=29 September 2016|work=The Times of India|date=25 June 2015}}</ref> ''Inter-district Master Aquatic Championship''<ref>{{cite news|title=Inter-district Master Aquatic Championship inaugurated.|url=http://www.thehansindia.com/posts/index/Andhra-Pradesh/2016-07-10/Inter-district-Master-Aquatic-Championship-inaugurated/241139|accessdate=29 September 2016|work=The Hans India|date=10 July 2016}}</ref> etc. The city was also a host for ''Khelo India programme'' for junior level national sports.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Correspondent|first1=Special|title=Khelo India: Nellore, Guntur chosen venues|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/andhra-pradesh/Khelo-India-Nellore-Guntur-chosen-venues/article16920349.ece|accessdate=15 January 2017|work=The Hindu}}</ref>\n\nInternational sports personalities from the city include: cricketer [[Ambati Rayudu]];<ref>{{cite web|title=Ambati Rayudu|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/india/content/player/33141.html|website=Cricinfo|accessdate=29 September 2016}}</ref> badminton player [[Srikanth Kidambi]], who won the  ''Super Series'' title in [[China]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jonathan|first1=P. Samuel|title=Guntur lad scripts history in badminton|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/andhra-pradesh/guntur-lad-scripts-history-in-badminton/article6605242.ece|accessdate=29 September 2016|work=The Hindu|date=17 November 2014}}</ref> and also finished as a quarter finalist at the [[2016 Summer Olympics]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bhatt|first1=Shephali|title=Srikanth Kidambi: On losing temporary limelight and keeping permanent focus on the game \u2013 The Economic Times|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/sports/srikanth-kidambi-on-losing-temporary-limelight-and-keeping-permanent-focus-on-the-game/articleshow/54500986.cms|accessdate=29 September 2016|work=The Economic Times|date=25 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Amaravati]]\n* [[List of cities in Andhra Pradesh]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Guntur}}\n{{Wikivoyage|Guntur City}}\n* [http://www.gunturcorporation.org/ Guntur Municipal Corporation]\n\n{{Guntur topics}}\n{{Guntur district}}\n{{Andhra Pradesh}}\n{{Mandal headquarters in Guntur district}}\n\n[[Category:Towns in Guntur district]]\n[[Category:Cities in Andhra Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Mandal headquarters in Guntur district]]\n[[Category:District headquarters of Andhra Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Guntur| ]]\n[[Category:Cities in Andhra Pradesh Capital Region]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Indian English|da